Motivated by the above analysis, we can implement HRA with an orthogonality regularizer. Typically, given a pre-trained model \(\mathcal{M}\), we can adapt \(L\) weight matrices of the model based on a dataset \(\mathcal{D}\) by solving the following optimization problem:

\[\min_{\{\bm{U}_{r}^{(l)}\}_{l=1}^{L}}\text{Loss}(\mathcal{D};\{\bm{U}_{r}^{(l )}\}_{l=1}^{L})+\lambda\sum\nolimits_{l=1}^{L}\|\bm{I}_{r}-(\bm{U}_{r}^{(l)} )^{\top}\bm{U}_{r}^{(l)}\|_{F}^{2},\] (6)

where \(\bm{U}_{r}^{(l)}\) denotes the parameters of HRA for the \(l\)-th weight matrix. In equation 6, the first term denotes the loss function, while the second term is the proposed regularizer that encourages the orthogonality of all \(\bm{U}_{r}^{(l)}\)'s, whose significance is controlled by \(\lambda>0\). Because it does not change the forward step of HRA, this regularizer only increases the adaptation cost slightly.

As shown in Figure 0(a), by controlling the strength of the orthogonality regularizer, we can achieve a trade-off between the model capacity and regularity. When \(\lambda=0\), the feasible domain of \(\bm{U}_{r}\) is the set of column-normalized matrices, and accordingly, the model capacity is maximized. In contrast, when \(\lambda\to\infty\), the feasible domain of \(\bm{U}_{r}\) is the set of orthogonal matrices (i.e., \(\mathbb{O}_{d\times r}\)), leading to the strongest regularity. When \(\lambda=\infty\), we implement a strictly-orthogonal HRA based on Gram-Schmidt (GS) orthogonalization. For each layer's HRA adapter, we initialize its parameter matrix as \(\bm{V}_{r}\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times r}\) and applying Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization [2] to it, i.e., \(\bm{U}_{r}=\text{GS}(\bm{V}_{r})\). As shown in Figure 0(a), in such a situation, the forward step of each adapter becomes \(\bm{z}=\bm{W}(\bm{I}-2\bm{U}_{r}\bm{U}_{r}^{\top})\bm{x}\), and the computational complexity becomes \(\mathcal{O}(d(r^{2}+r+d_{\text{out}}))\), where additional \(\mathcal{O}(dr^{2})\) operations are used for Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization. According to Table 1, the complexity of this strictly-orthogonal HRA is comparable to OFT [37] when \(r=b\).

