## Appendix A The Impacts of Orthogonality

Given a weight matrix \(\bm{W}\in\mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{out}}\times d}\), we assume that \(d_{\text{out}}\geq d\). Denote the SVD of \(\bm{W}\) as \(\bm{Q}\bm{\Sigma}\bm{V}^{\top}\), where \(\bm{\Sigma}=\text{diag}(\sigma_{1},...,\sigma_{d})\), \(\sigma_{1}\geq\sigma_{2}\geq...\geq\sigma_{d}\), and \(\bm{V}=[\bm{v}_{1},...,\bm{v}_{d}]\) is the right singular matrix.

When \(r=1\), we have

\[\|\bm{W}-\bm{W}\bm{H}^{(1)}\|_{F}^{2}=4\|\bm{W}\bm{u}_{1}\bm{u}_{1}^{\top}\|_{F }^{2}=4\text{tr}(\bm{u}_{1}^{\top}\bm{V}\bm{\Sigma}^{2}\bm{V}\bm{u}_{1}),\text { for }\bm{u}_{1}\in\mathbb{S}^{d-1}.\] (7)

Obviously, when \(\bm{u}_{1}=\bm{v}_{1}\), the distance between \(\bm{W}\) and \(\bm{W}\bm{H}^{(1)}\) is maximized.

Applying mathematical induction, we assume that \(\|\bm{W}-\bm{W}\bm{H}^{(r)}\|_{F}\) is maximized when \(\bm{U}_{r}=\bm{V}_{r}=[\bm{v}_{1},...,\bm{v}_{r}]\) for \(r<d\).

Then, in the case of \(r+1\), for \(\bm{u}\in\mathbb{S}^{d-1}\), we have

\[\|\bm{W}-\bm{W}\bm{H}^{(r+1)}\|_{F}^{2}=\|\bm{W}-\bm{W}\bm{H}^{(r)}(\bm{I}-2 \bm{u}\bm{u}^{\top})\|_{F}^{2}=4\|\bm{W}\bm{V}_{r}\bm{V}_{r}^{\top}-\bm{W}\bm{ u}\bm{u}^{\top}\|_{F}^{2},\] (8)

where the equations are based on the facts that \(i)\) HR and the chain of HRs are unitary matrices and \(ii)\) the Frobenius norm is unitary-invariant.

Note that, \(\bm{V}=[\bm{v}_{1},...,\bm{v}_{d}]=[\bm{V}_{r},\bm{V}_{d-r}]\) works as an orthonormal basis of \(\mathbb{R}^{d}\), so we have \(\bm{u}=\bm{V}\bm{\beta}=\bm{V}_{r}\bm{\beta}_{r}+\bm{V}_{d-r}\bm{\beta}_{d-r}\), where \(\bm{\beta}=[\bm{\beta}_{r};\bm{\beta}_{d-r}]\in\mathbb{S}^{d-1}\). Accordingly, we rewrite equation 8 as

\[\|\bm{W}-\bm{W}\bm{H}^{(r+1)}\|_{F}^{2}\] \[= 4\|\bm{W}\bm{V}_{r}\bm{V}_{r}^{\top}-\bm{W}\bm{u}\bm{u}^{\top}\| _{F}^{2}\] \[= 4\|\bm{\Sigma}\bm{V}^{\top}\bm{V}_{r}\bm{V}_{r}^{\top}-\bm{\Sigma }\bm{V}^{\top}\bm{u}\bm{u}^{\top}\|_{F}^{2}\] \[= 4\text{tr}([\bm{V}_{r},\bm{0}_{d\times(d-r)}]\bm{\Sigma}^{2}[\bm{ V}_{r},\bm{0}_{d\times(d-r)}]^{\top})-8\text{tr}([\bm{V}_{r},\bm{0}_{d\times(d-r)}] \bm{\Sigma}^{2}\bm{V}^{\top}\bm{u}\bm{u}^{\top})+4\text{tr}(\bm{u}^{\top}\bm{ V}\bm{\Sigma}^{2}\bm{V}^{\top}\bm{u})\] \[= 4\sum\nolimits_{i=1}^{r}\sigma_{i}^{2}+4\text{tr}(\bm{\beta}^{ \top}\bm{\Sigma}^{2}\bm{\beta})-8\text{tr}(\bm{\beta}_{r}^{\top}\bm{\Sigma}_{ r}^{2}\bm{\beta}_{r})\] \[= 4\sum\nolimits_{i=1}^{r}\sigma_{i}^{2}+4\text{tr}(\bm{\beta}_{d -r}^{\top}\bm{\Sigma}_{d-r}^{2}\bm{\beta}_{d-r})-4\text{tr}(\bm{\beta}_{r}^{ \top}\bm{\Sigma}_{r}^{2}\bm{\beta}_{r}),\]

where \(\bm{\Sigma}=\text{diag}(\bm{\Sigma}_{r},\bm{\Sigma}_{d-r})\). Obviously, when \(\bm{\beta}_{r}=\bm{0}_{r}\) and \(\bm{\beta}_{d-r}=[1,0,..,0]^{\top}\in\mathbb{R}^{d-r}\), the distance between \(\bm{W}\) and \(\bm{W}\bm{H}^{(r+1)}\) is maximized. In such a situation, \(\bm{u}=\bm{V}\bm{\beta}=\bm{v}_{r+1}\), corresponds to the \((r+1)\)-th right singular vector, and \(\bm{U}_{t+1}=\bm{V}_{t+1}\) accordingly.

